This is a unique chapel, in the shape and the presence of an oculus in the dome.  It originally was connected to a convent.   Now it is a protestant church.   The building is beautiful and there are some silk hangings made by a parishoner decorating the interior.

A place steeped in history, a mecca of French Protestantism when Protestants still protested without compromising the spirit of the times. Very beautiful architecture which deserves continued renovation work. Basis of many social actions in the concrete implementation of love of neighbor. For worship times, see the website.

I was lucky enough to stay at a hotel across the street from this hotel, and was able to see this church illuminated by the morning sun every day from my room window. Apparently you can go inside on Sunday, but I didn't get to see it because I returned to Japan on Saturday.
Great community with committed Christians and serving pastors who have been working for many years to bring this beautiful Church to life.

This comment only refers to the exterior of the building, since I have not yet managed to visit it. It is a Protestant temple, the former church of a convent that does not exist today, founded in 1634. During the revolution it was used as a book warehouse, and was given to the Protestant cult in 1802. Its design is inspired by the pantheon of Rome. It has a circular plan with five chapels. The entrance is from the north, and the altar is to the south, a rare situation in churches of Catholic origin, which are usually oriented towards the east.
Beautiful church and beautiful community, with people remarkable in their service to others.
Interesting to see with its double dome.

Excellent welcome in a beautiful building. Our daughter was able to be looked after with other children during worship. Thanks to this, we had time to meditate on the Word and our daughter had a great time. A beautiful and warm community. We'll come back!
A beautiful building which invites human beings to a moment of contemplation.

The Temple du Marais is a very beautiful Protestant Church, located close to Place de la Bastille. The decoration and architecture are impressively beautiful. It is open to the public on Sundays for worship. A great visiting option for tourists, Protestants or not.

This beautiful building, both pompous and familiar, pleasantly punctuates the venerable rue Saint-Antoine. It is one of the few circular churches in Paris, including the Notre-Dame de l'Assomption church, rue Saint-Honor√© and, of course, the former chapel of the Coll√®ge des Quatre-Nations founded Mazarin, now a "dome " of the French Academy.

We came to this small church by chance because it is Protestant. Inside we were greeted warmly in French. We identified ourselves as tourists in English. An older lady asked us in English where we were from. "From Germany." "Ah, Germans." Afterwards we received a short lecture from her on church history in very good German. That surprised us very positively. Unfortunately we didn't have time to come to the service the next day, but we'll be happy to do so on our next visit. Thank you madame

Magnificent place! For a visit, or for listening, or for spiritual renewal, or for a simple little break... Finally! For any occasion, there is always someone. And everyone is nice! It‚Äôs a change from everyday life, from this Paris where everyone is bitter!

The building was a church from 1632 until the French Revolution of 1789. It is in Baroque style and was part of the Convent of the Visitation of Sainte-Marie. During the period of the revolution, it served as a book depository. By decree of the first consul Bonaparte on 03/12/1802, the church was assigned to Reformed worship and became a Protestant temple, bearing the name of Sainte-Marie temple.

Very beautiful building from 1638 made by students of Mansard. built on the occasion of the birth of the future dolphin Louis 14 . unfortunately under construction for a few months inside the stone blocks having detached from the dome without causing any injuries
